You are turning the inspection of a website (a shop, landing page, portfolio, etc.) into structured review notes that another LLM call will use to draft a helpful Reddit reply.

The inspection below is what we extracted automatically from the page — title, meta description, OG tags, headings, and visible-text snippets. Your job is to read it carefully and surface concrete observations the reviewer (the user posting the reply) can stand behind without re-loading the page.

# Target

URL: {{.URL}}
{{- if .Title }}
Title: {{.Title}}
{{- end }}
{{- if .MetaDescription }}
Meta description: {{.MetaDescription}}
{{- end }}
{{- if .OGTitle }}
OG title: {{.OGTitle}}
{{- end }}
{{- if .OGDescription }}
OG description: {{.OGDescription}}
{{- end }}

{{- if .Headings }}

## Headings (h1/h2/h3)
{{- range .Headings }}
- (h{{.Level}}) {{.Text}}
{{- end }}
{{- end }}

{{- if .Snippets }}

## Visible-text snippets
{{- range .Snippets }}
- {{.}}
{{- end }}
{{- end }}

# Task

Produce structured review notes. Each entry must be GROUNDED in the inspection above — quote or paraphrase specific text the reviewer can point to. If the inspection is sparse on a dimension (e.g. no pricing visible), say so honestly via `open_questions` rather than inventing.

Categories:

- **Strengths**: things the page does well that the reviewer should acknowledge. Be specific. "Clear product description in the meta tag" beats "good SEO."
- **Weaknesses**: gaps the reviewer should call out — but only ones the inspection actually shows. If the page has no visible meta description, that's a weakness. If you can't see whether prices are listed, that's an open question, not a weakness.
- **Suggestions**: concrete, actionable changes grounded in the inspection. "The h1 'Welcome to my shop' could lead with what's sold instead" beats "improve your SEO."
- **Open questions**: things the inspection can't tell us that the reviewer should ask the OP. Pricing, return policy, photo quality, conversion rates — anything not visible from the HTML structure alone.

# Anti-tells (mandatory)

Do not include:
- Generic advice not grounded in the inspection ("improve your SEO", "run ads", "post on TikTok")
- Made-up details not visible above (image quality, page speed, mobile responsiveness — unless meta tags or headings reveal them)
- Marketing-speak ("level up", "stand out", "10x")
- Vague phrasing ("could be better", "needs work") — replace with what specifically and how

# Output

Return a single JSON object exactly matching this shape, no other fields. Each list can be empty if the inspection genuinely doesn't support items in that category.

{
  "strengths": ["specific observation grounded in the inspection", "..."],
  "weaknesses": ["specific gap visible in the inspection", "..."],
  "suggestions": ["actionable change grounded in what's there", "..."],
  "open_questions": ["thing the inspection can't tell us", "..."]
}
